1 A Summary of current Cross Slice Comparison Methods

Rank Method Category Approach Spatial-Aware Key Advantage Performance Score Best Use Case
1 PASTE Alignment Optimal Transport Yes Perfect spot-to-spot mapping (1.0 ratio) 9.5/10 Adjacent slice alignment
2 SPACEL Alignment Deep Learning + GCN Yes Highest layer-wise accuracy (85%) 9.2/10 3D reconstruction
3 STAligner Integration Graph Attention Yes Best batch correction, scalable 9.0/10 Multi-sample integration
4 CAST Cross-sample Deep GNN Yes Single-cell resolution across samples 9.2/10 Cross-technology alignment
5 PRECAST Integration Bayesian Framework Yes Statistical rigor, uncertainty quantification 8.5/10 Multi-sample Bayesian analysis
6 STalign Alignment Diffeomorphic Mapping Yes Cross-platform compatibility 8.2/10 Technology integration
7 DeepST Integration Graph AutoEncoder Yes Significant ARI improvement (+0.11) 8.0/10 Domain identification enhancement
8 PASTE2 Alignment Partial Optimal Transport Yes Handles partial tissue overlap 7.8/10 Partial overlap scenarios
9 Seurat Integration scRNA Adaptation Mutual Nearest Neighbors No Familiar workflow, widely used 6.5/10 Biological replicates only
10 SPIRAL Integration Graph + Optimal Transport Yes All-to-all alignment capability 6.0/10 Complex multi-slice scenarios
11 GPSA Alignment Gaussian Process Yes Probabilistic framework 5.8/10 Small datasets with uncertainty
12 Scanorama scRNA Integration Batch Correction No General batch effect removal 4.0/10 Not recommended for spatial
Rank Method Cross-Tech Score Supported Technologies Key Strength Limitations
1 CAST 10/10 Visium, STARmap, MERFISH, RIBOmap, Slide-seq, Stereo-seq Single-cell resolution across all platforms Very new (2024), limited validation
2 STalign 9/10 Visium, MERFISH, Slide-seq, STARmap Diffeomorphic mapping handles coordinate differences Complex parameter tuning
3 SANTO 8.5/10 10x Xenium, Visium, subcellular platforms Coarse-to-fine handles resolution differences Requires overlapping regions
4 STAligner 8/10 Multiple platforms via graph attention Scalable across technologies Limited to similar gene panels
5 SpatialGlue 7.5/10 Multi-modal spatial platforms Handles different data modalities Requires paired multi-omics data
6 DeepST 6/10 Limited cross-platform capability Graph networks adapt to different inputs Not specifically designed for cross-tech
7 SPIRAL 5.5/10 Some cross-platform support Optimal transport framework Poor performance on distant platforms
8 SPACEL 5/10 Primarily Visium-focused Good 3D reconstruction Limited cross-technology validation
9 PASTE 4/10 Similar technologies only (Visium-Visium) Excellent for same platform Fails with different coordinate systems
10 PRECAST 4/10 Limited cross-platform Bayesian framework flexible Not designed for technology differences
11 GPSA 3/10 Minimal cross-technology support Probabilistic approach Poor scalability across platforms
12 Seurat Integration 2/10 Same format data only Familiar workflow No cross-technology awareness

1.0.1 Key Findings:

  • PASTE and SPACEL dominate for spatial alignment tasks
  • Seurat Integration ranks 9th - significantly worse than spatial-specific methods
  • Marker gene recovery: PASTE (427) vs Seurat (1852) = 4.3x better performance
  • Spatial methods consistently outperform adapted scRNA-seq methods
  • Seurat Integration should only be used for biological replicates or quick exploration

Rankings based on comprehensive benchmarks from Genome Biology 2024, Nature Methods 2022-2024, and spatial omics literature.

Best performance indicators marked with asterisk ()

2 Seurat Integration (CCA/RPCA)

Aligns image. Remove technical effect

Finds anchor cells/spots that are similar across different datasets. Then Uses the anchors to align gene expression across datasets

Why do we need it?

Click for Details

Without integration same cell types look different across slices due to:

Technical batch effects - Different sequencing depths - Processing variations

With integration Same cell types cluster together regardless of which slice they came from.

Simple analogy: FindIntegrationAnchors = Find matching landmarks across different maps IntegrateData = Use landmarks to align all maps into one coherent map

Code 
if (!file.exists(file.path(workDir, "/data/processed", "spatial.Seurat.integrated.preDim.RDS"))) {
# Integration using Seurat
# Step 1: Select integration features
## Selects highly variable genes that are consistently variable across multiple datasets
## Reduces Noise: Filters out genes that are not informative for integration

features <- SelectIntegrationFeatures( 
  object.list = spatial_list
  , nfeatures = 3000
) 

# Step 2:ReNormalise on spatially informative genes.
spatial_list <- lapply(
  spatial_list
  , function(obj) {
    SCTransform(
      obj
      , assay = "Spatial"
      , method = "poisson"
      , variable.features.n = 3000
      , verbose = FALSE
      , return.only.var.genes = FALSE  # Critical parameter
    )
  }
)

# Step 3: Re-select features after SCTransform
features <- SelectIntegrationFeatures(
  object.list = spatial_list
  , nfeatures = 2000
)

# Step 4: Prepare SCT integration
spatial_list <- PrepSCTIntegration(
  object.list = spatial_list
  , anchor.features = features
)

# Step 5: integration anchors
spatial.anchors <- FindIntegrationAnchors(
  object.list = spatial_list
  , normalization.method = "SCT"
  , anchor.features = features
  , dims = 1:30
)

# Step 6:Integrate data
spatial.integrated <- IntegrateData(
  anchorset = spatial.anchors
  , normalization.method = "SCT"
  , dims = 1:30
)

# Switch to integrated assay for downstream analysis
DefaultAssay(spatial.integrated) <- "integrated"

  saveRDS(spatial.integrated, file.path(workDir, "/data/processed", "spatial.Seurat.integrated.preDim.RDS"))
} else  {
  spatial.integrated <- readRDS(file.path(workDir, "/data/processed", "spatial.Seurat.integrated.preDim.RDS"))
}

2.1 Response and QC visualizations

Code 
if (!file.exists(file.path(workDir, "/data/processed", "spatial.Seurat.integrated.RDS"))) {
  
  # Scale integrated data
  spatial.integrated <- ScaleData(
    spatial.integrated
    , verbose = FALSE
  )
  
  # Run PCA
  spatial.integrated <- RunPCA(
    spatial.integrated
    , npcs = 50
    , verbose = FALSE
  )
  
  # Determine optimal number of PCs
  ElbowPlot(
    spatial.integrated
    , ndims = 50
  )
  
  # Run UMAP
  spatial.integrated <- RunUMAP(
    spatial.integrated
    , reduction = "pca"
    , dims = 1:15
    , verbose = FALSE
  )
  
  # Find neighbors and clusters
  spatial.integrated <- FindNeighbors(
    spatial.integrated
    , reduction = "pca"
    , dims = 1:15
    , verbose = FALSE
  )
  
  spatial.integrated <- FindClusters(
    spatial.integrated
    , resolution = c(0.1, 0.3, 0.5, 0.8, 1.0)
    , verbose = FALSE
  )
  
  saveRDS(spatial.integrated, file.path(workDir, "/data/processed", "spatial.Seurat.integrated.RDS"))
} else  {
  spatial.integrated <- readRDS(file.path(workDir, "/data/processed", "spatial.Seurat.integrated.RDS"))
}

2.3 Integration QC

Code 
# Check integration quality with key metrics
integration_metrics <- list()

# Calculate silhouette scores for integration (using optimal PCs)
pca_embeddings <- Embeddings(spatial.integrated, reduction = "pca")[, 1:15]
sample_labels <- as.numeric(as.factor(spatial.integrated$orig.ident))
sil_scores <- silhouette(sample_labels, dist(pca_embeddings))
integration_metrics$silhouette_score <- mean(sil_scores[, 3])

# Plot silhouette analysis
plot(sil_scores, col = 1:length(unique(sample_labels)), border = NA)

Figure 2.1: Most silhouette scores are negative for Samples 1-5, meaning spots have high cross sample similarity than within sample similar. I.e. no batch effect. Lower is better

2.4 Marker Gene Identification

Code 
# Switch to SCT assay for DE analysis (if SCTransform was used)
DefaultAssay(spatial.integrated) <- "SCT"
Idents(spatial.integrated) <- "response"

# Because there are a different noice model per sample, we need to normalise this across samples
spatial.integrated.dctf <- PrepSCTFindMarkers(spatial.integrated)

library(future)
options(future.globals.maxSize = 16000 * 1024^2)  # 8GB limit
plan("sequential") 

response_degs  <- FindMarkers(
  spatial.integrated.dctf
  , ident.1 = "Responder"
  , ident.2 = "Non-Responder" 
  , logfc.threshold = 0.1                              
  , min.pct = 0.25
  , test.use = "wilcox"
  , verbose = FALSE
)

# Display 
# Add gene names and significance
response_degs$gene <- rownames(response_degs)
response_degs$significance <- ifelse(response_degs$p_val_adj < 0.05, "Significant", "Not Significant")
response_degs$direction <- ifelse(response_degs$avg_log2FC > 0, "Higher_in_Responders", "Higher_in_Non_Responders")

response_degs %>%
  filter(avg_log2FC > 0, p_val_adj < 0.05) %>%
  arrange(desc(avg_log2FC)) %>%
  head(10) %>% 
  dplyr::select(-direction) %>% 
  knitr::kable(caption="Top 10 Responder specific genes"
  )

# Extract expression matrix
expr_matrix <- as.matrix(GetAssayData(
  spatial.integrated.dctf
  , assay = "SCT"    # or "Spatial"
  , slot = "data"    # normalized data
))[top_degs$gene, ]

# Create annotation dataframe for columns (cells)
annotation_col <- data.frame(
  Response_Status = spatial.integrated.dctf$response
  , Sample = spatial.integrated.dctf$orig.ident
)
rownames(annotation_col) <- colnames(expr_matrix)

# Create annotation colors
annotation_colors <- list(
  Response_Status = c("Responder" = "#2E8B57", "Non-Responder" = "#CD5C5C"),
  Sample = rainbow(length(unique(spatial.integrated$orig.ident)))
)
names(annotation_colors$Sample) <- unique(spatial.integrated.dctf$orig.ident)

# Create pheatmap
pheatmap(
  as.matrix(expr_matrix)
  , annotation_col = annotation_col
  , annotation_colors = annotation_colors
  , cluster_rows = T
  , cluster_cols = F
  , show_colnames = FALSE            # Don't show cell names
  , show_rownames = TRUE             # Show gene names
  , fontsize_row = 8
  , fontsize_col = 6
  , border_color = NA
  , main = "Response DEGs Heatmap"
)
